The Netlify deploy errored, with the following guidance provided:

Diagnosis
- Relevant error lines: [line 21](#L21), [line 24](#L24), [line 25](#L25), [line 30](#L30), [line 34](#L34), [line 36](#L36), [lines 40–42](#L40-L42), and the final failure [line 48–49](#L48-L49).
- Error type: npm ERESOLVE — a peer dependency conflict during npm install.
- Cause: Your project depends on next@14.2.35 (see [line 25](#L25)), while @clerk/nextjs@7.0.4 requires Next.js v15 or v16 (see [line 30](#L30)). npm cannot resolve that peer requirement, so install fails ([lines 40–42](#L40-L42)).

Solution
1. Verify current versions are committed
   - Confirm package.json in the repo contains the Next and Clerk packages and has been committed: https://github.com/LikkleOra/LexisLaw/blob/master/package.json
   - If package.json or any change is missing locally, commit it before pushing.

2. Recommended fix (preferred): upgrade Next to a Clerk-compatible version
   - @clerk/nextjs@7.0.4 requires Next >= v15.2.8 or v16.x. Upgrade Next to a matching release (for example 16.1.7).
   - Steps:
     - Locally run:
       ```bash
       npm install next@^16.1.7 --save
       npm install
       npm run build
       ```
     - If local build succeeds, commit the updated package.json and package-lock.json and push to the repo. Netlify will then re-run the build.

   - Notes:
     - Upgrading Next may require code changes for breaking changes between Next 14 → 15/16. Test locally and address any migration issues before deploying.

3. Alternative fix (if you cannot upgrade Next): use a Clerk version that supports Next 14
   - Find a @clerk/nextjs release compatible with Next 14 (check Clerk’s docs/changelog), then update package.json to that older @clerk/nextjs version and run npm install locally.
   - Example (illustrative — verify correct compatible version before applying):
     ```bash
     npm install @clerk/nextjs@<compatible-version> --save
     npm install
     npm run build
     ```
   - Commit and push package.json/package-lock.json when successful.

4. Temporary/workaround (not recommended for long term)
   - Allow npm to ignore peer conflicts by using legacy peer deps. This may lead to runtime issues:
     - Change the Netlify install step to run with --legacy-peer-deps, e.g. set your build command or environment so that npm runs with:
       ```bash
       npm install --legacy-peer-deps
       npm run build
       ```
     - Or set the environment variable NPM_FLAGS="--legacy-peer-deps" in Netlify build settings.
   - Use this only to unblock deployment while you prepare a proper version alignment.

Summary checklist
- Verify package.json is present and committed (link above).
- Preferred: upgrade Next to a version that satisfies @clerk/nextjs (e.g. ^16.1.7), test locally, commit and push.
- Or: pick a Clerk version compatible with Next 14, test locally, commit and push.
- Avoid long-term use of --legacy-peer-deps except as a last-resort temporary workaround.

